{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"CP – Assumptions","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1. The Cell Phenotype domain captures cell phenotyping and related data based on cell expression markers and other indicators (e.g., stains/dyes) in disseminated tissue specimens and cell suspensions.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2. The CP domain is only used for tests which include a phenotyping component that relies on using cell markers to identify a specific population of cells (e.g., quantitative cell phenotyping), or on which the test is conducted (e.g., quantitative single marker expression, target/receptor occupancy). For example, a test which measures gamma-interferon expression in helper T lymphocytes defined as the CD45+CD3+CD4+CD8- population is an appropriate test for including in CP, whereas a test which measures gamma interferon secretion in an undefined \"PBMC\" (peripheral blood mononuclear cell) population is not appropriate.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3. A value which is calculated and reported by a lab according to its procedures is considered collected rather than derived; the Derived Flag (CPDRVFL) should be null for these results.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"4. CPCELSTA is used in conjunction with CPCSMRKS. When CPCELSTA is populated, CPCSMRKS must also be populated. Conversely, when CPCSMRKS is populated, CPCELSTA must be populated.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"5. The combination of values in CPTEST, CPSBMRKS, CPCELSTA, and CPCSMRKS are used to uniquely identify a test. When 1 or more of the variables CPSBMRKS, CPCELSTA, or CPCSMRKS are populated, the Test Name (CPTEST) must be populated with the test name variant containing the \"Sub\" suffix to indicate that the finding/result pertains to a subpopulation of the cell type named in CPTEST.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"6. Populating the CPTEST and CPMRKSTR variables: The general structure of CPTEST depends on the use case (e.g., immunophenotyping, quantitative marker expression, target/receptor occupancy), which is generally conveyed by the CPCAT and/or CPSCAT value(s). Currently, CP supports the following use cases for which guidance on CPTEST and CPMRKSTR values are given:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a. Immunophenotyping","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i. CPTEST is populated with the name of the cell type being measured, not with the set of markers used to define the cell type.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii. It is expected that CPMRKSTR is populated, and that it contains the entire set of markers used to define the test, including those that are also present in CPSBMRKS and/or CPCSMRKS.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iii. Marker strings follow, as closely as possible, formatting recommendations presented in assumption 8.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. Quantitative single-marker expression","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i. CPTEST begins with the identity of the marker (e.g., CD99), followed by the word \"Expression\" (e.g., \"CD99 Expression\").","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii. It is expected that CPMRKSTR is populated, and that it starts by identifying the marker being quantified (e.g. \"CD99\"). This is followed by a delimiter (described below) and then the entire marker string used to define the cell population on which the marker is measured, including the marker being quantified, since it also defines the cell population.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iii. The general form of the delimiter used to separate the marker being quantified from the cell population on which it is measured is \"<space>xxxx<space>\", where \"xxxx\" represents a character string used as delimiting text. It is recommended that the delimiting text is the abbreviation for the unit of measure used to report the level of expression of the quantified marker (e.g., \"MESF\", \"MdFI\"). An example which follows this guidance is: CPTEST = \"CD99 Expression\" and CPMRKSTR = \"CD99 MESF CD45+CD3-CD19+CD99+\", where \"MESF\" is the text delimiter and is followed by the entire marker string defining the cell population on which CD99 was measured, which includes the CD99 marker itself.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iv. Marker strings follow, as closely as possible, formatting recommendations presented in assumption 8.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0205_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":205,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"c. Other use cases (e.g., target/receptor occupancy), refer to the examples section and to published Controlled Terminology supporting CP. In the case of target/receptor occupancy a more generalized test value is populated into CPTEST (e.g., \"Total Bound\") and the identity of the target/receptor is","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21a","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a001", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "included in another variable, such as CPBNDAGT and/or CPTSTPNL (refer to examples). CDISC will continue to develop examples for other use cases as they are identified and modeled.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a002", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "7. Specifying viability:", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a003", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "a. Because the majority of cell phenotyping tests of interest are for viable cells, the word \"Viable\" is not generally included in the test name (CPTEST) and usually does not need to be explicitly stated in CPCELSTA. Because populating CPCELSTA and CSMRKS with viability information necessitates appending the \"Sub\" suffix to the value in CPTEST (assumption 5), it is recommended that CPCELSTA and CPCSMRKS generally not be used unless a selective viability stain was included in the test in order to differentiate the record for viable cells from record(s) for cells in a different vital state. For example, when viable cells are being compared to apoptotic and/or non-viable cells, it is necessary to differentiate those records using CPCELSTA and CPCSMRKS. In such cases where CPCELSTA and CPCSMRKS are populated, the \"Sub\" suffix is appended to the value in CPTEST (assumption 5).", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a004", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "b. Viability marker(s) used to define a test are included in the full marker string in CPMRKSTR regardless of whether the viability status is stated explicitly in CPCELSTA. Moreover, if viability is explicitly stated in CPGATE, marker(s) used to designate viability are included in CPGATDEF. For example, if the value in CPGATE is \"Lymphocytes, Viable\" and 7AAD- was used to define the viable state, 7AAD- is included in CPGATDEF, in addition to being included in the complete marker string in CPMRKSTR.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a005", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "8. Recommended formatting of marker string variables CPMRKSTR, CPSBMRKS, and CPCSMRKS: The marker string variables provide critical information for defining a test. Although there are no current plans to control their values through CDISC Controlled Terminology codelists, adherence to the following formatting guidelines helps to preclude ambiguities that can lead to uncertainty in uniquely understanding a test and its associated result.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a006", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "a. Marker strings do not contain delimiting characters (e.g., \",\", space, \"/\", \"|\") to separate individual markers within the string, nor do they contain punctuation (e.g., hyphens) within individual markers, as these can be confused with symbols used to designate levels of expression and/or make it difficult to distinguish between the individual markers that comprise the string. For example, although the scientific literature often uses \"HLA-DR\", this is represented in CP marker strings as \"HLADR\".", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a007", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "b. Forward slash \"/\" is only used to separate the portion of the marker string defining a numerator from the portion defining a denominator.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a008", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "c. When referring to a marker using the cluster of differentiation (CD) designation, \"CD\" should be included as part of the marker reference. For example, a marker string for helper T lymphocytes comprising CD45, CD3, CD4, and CD8 markers would be \"CD45+CD3+CD4+CD8-\" (rather than \"45+3+4+8-\").", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0206_a009", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 206, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "d. The order of markers within a string is consistent across similar tests, generally proceeding in the order that defines the cell hierarchy from highest to lowest, followed by additional non-lineage-defining markers, and ending with cell state and viability markers. This order maintains alignment with how a test is identified using the ordered combination of CPTEST, CPSMRKS, and CPCELSTA. For example, a test for proliferating viable activated central memory helper T-lymphocytes would be operationally defined in CPMRKSTR as similar to \"CD45+CD3+CD19-CD4+CD8-CD197+CD45RA-CD278+Ki67+7AAD-\", where the order of markers in the string is \"CD45\" (leukocyte), \"CD3+CD19- (T lymphocyte), \"CD4+CD8-\" (helper), \"CD197+CD45RA-\" (central memory), \"CD278+\" (activated), Ki67+ (proliferating), 7AAD- (viable). Corresponding to this marker-based definition of the test, and using the appropriate Controlled Terminology terms, CPTEST is \"TLym Help Cen Mem Sub\", CPCELSTA is \"ACTIVATED; PROLIFERATING\", and CPCSMRKS is \"CD278+Ki67+\". If the sponsor also chose to include the viability status as a cell state in addition to the activation and proliferative states, CPCELSTA would be similar to \"ACTIVATED; PROLIFERATING; VIABLE\" and the corresponding CPCSMRKS value would be \"CD278+Ki67+7AAD-\". In this example, the named cell population in CPTEST has not been further divided into an unnamed sublineage based on additional sublineage markers; therefore, CPSBMRKS is null.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a001", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "e. Forward (FSC) and Side (SSC) light scatter: These parameters are generally used to perform initial gating to exclude debris non-singlets and are often reapplied to differentiate cell subpopulations in the \"inclusion\" gate. However, FSC and SSC are often not included in marker string definitions as it is generally taken for granted that they were used. In contrast, they are usually included in a descriptions of a gating strategy, and would generally be included in CPGATDEF when the full gating strategy is shown. Labs/sponsors may choose whether to include FSC and SSC parameters in CPMRKSTR. It is recommended to include them when they are needed to differentiate one test from another. For example, because there is no universal expression marker specific for lymphocytes, FSC and SSC are used to define the lymphocyte subpopulation within a CD45+ leukocyte population. A test of \"Lymphocytes/Leukocytes\" defined only in terms of CD45 expression would not make sense as it would be \"CD45+/CD45+\". In this case, it makes sense to define lymphocytes as \"CD45+SSClo\" so that the value in CPMRKSTR is \"CD45+SSClo/CD45+\".", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a002", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "f. Indicating the expression level of individual markers included in a marker string: A variety of formats are used in the scientific literature for indicating the level of expression of a marker on or within a cell. For example, after identifying a marker such as CD4, its level of expression might be represented as 1 of the following:", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a003", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "i. neg, min, or - to denote the absence or minimal expression (e.g., CD4neg, CD4min, CD4-)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a004", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "ii. pos or + to denote that the marker is expressed (e.g., CD4pos, CD4+)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a005", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "iii. high, hi, or ++ to denote that the marker is expressed at a very high level relative to simply being \"positive\" (e.g., CD4high, CD4hi, CD4++)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a006", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "iv. other formats (e.g., -/low, -/lo, low, lo, mid, -/+, +++)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a007", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "g. Because categories for expression levels are subjective in the sense that they are relative to one another, various formats often overlap, which can create ambiguities. Some degree of consistency in formats used to represent relative expression levels is warranted to mitigate ambiguity, at least to the extent that relative expression levels used to define cell lineages/sublineages are similar across studies and laboratories in order to enable comparisons. Five designations are recommended for use in SDTM datasets:", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a008", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "i. \"-\" (the marker is not expressed; at times, the use of \"-lo\" may be justified to indicate that the marker is either not expressed or is present in a negligible amount)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a009", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "ii. \"lo\" (the marker is expressed at a low level)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a010", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "iii. \"mid\" (the marker is expressed somewhere between a low and \"normal\" positive level for that cell type)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a011", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "iv. \"+\" (the marker is expressed at a normal positive level for that cell type)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a012", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "v. \"hi\" (the marker is expressed at a distinctly higher level than in cells that are \"+\", such that they are distinguishable from the \"+\" population and define their own subpopulation)", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a013", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "vi. Although these designations are expected to be useful in the majority of cases, it is recognized that designations not listed here may be more appropriate in some cases. The data provider must determine the best way to designate an expression level suited to the purpose of the test, while striving to mitigate ambiguities resulting from lack of consistency of use.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0207_a014", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 207, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "h. Explicitly indicating the cellular sublocation for a marker: In most cases, the location of a marker on or within a cell is not necessary; however, there are situations in which a marker can be expressed in more than a single cellular compartment and there is a need for the test to distinguish between marker expression in one compartment versus another. To accommodate this, using a lowercase letter in front of the marker is recommended. The cell sublocations are usually related to the cell surface (plasma membrane), cytoplasm, and nucleus. Use m, c, or n in front of the marker to denote \"membrane\", \"cytoplasm\", and \"nucleus\", respectively. An example of a marker often associated with a need to indicate cell location is CD152 (CTLA4), where cytoplasmic expression may define a test to distinguish it from whole cell expression. In this case, \"cCD152\" is used to denote that it is the cytoplasmic expression of CD152 that is measured for the test.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a001", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "9. CPNRIND can be added to indicate where a result falls with respect to a reference range defined by CPORNRLO and CPORNRHI (e.g., \"HIGH\", \"LOW\").", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a002", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "10. The variable CPORRESU uses the UNIT codelist. This means that sponsors should be submitting a term from the CDISC Submission Value column in the published Controlled Terminology maintained for CDISC by NCI EVS. When sponsors have units that are not in this column, they should first check to see if their unit is mathematically synonymous with an existing unit and submit their lab values using that unit. If this is not the case, then a request for a new term (see https://ncitermform.nci.nih.gov/) should be submitted.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a003", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "CP – Examples", "heading_level": 5, "sibling_index": 4, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a004", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "The CP domain includes use of several new qualifier variables.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a005", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "The primary intent of the following examples is to demonstrate the appropriate use of these new variables based on a selection of use cases for which they would ordinarily be included in a well-structured CP dataset.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a006", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Secondarily, the examples illustrate standardized formatting concepts for variables that are not associated with a formal Controlled Terminology codelist.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a007", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Although not controlled, the standardized formatting of content for these variables significantly aids understanding of the test and associated data, making data review and comparisons much easier.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a008", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "To make the examples as easy to understand as possible, many of the other SDTM variables that would normally be included in the dataset and which are already familiar to the reader have not been included.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a009", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "The following new SDTM variables are included in the examples: CPSBMRKS (Sublineage Marker String), CPCELSTA (Cell State), CPCSMRKS (Cell State Marker String), CPTSTCND (Test Condition), CPCNDAGT (Test Condition Agent), CPBDAGNT (Binding Agent), CPABCLID (Antibody Clone Identifier), CPMRKSTR (Marker String), CPGATE (Gate), CPGATDEF (Gate Definition), CPSPTSTD (Sponsor Test Description), CPTSTPNL (Test Panel), CPRESSCL (Result Scale), CPRESTYP (Result Type), and CPCOLSRT (Collected Summary Result Type).", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a010", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "The proper use of each of these variables is illustrated in 1 or more of the examples, based on the identified use case.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a011", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "Example 1", "heading_level": 6, "sibling_index": 1, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a012", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Example 1a illustrates use of the CPMRKSTR variable for an assay panel that enumerates several of the major named cell subpopulations of leukocytes.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a013", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "For most cases involving simple phenotyping, and when used in accordance with CP domain guidance, the CPMRKSTR variable is sufficient for providing the marker information needed to fully describe a test.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a014", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "As such, CPMRKSTR is the only new CP test qualifier variable having a Core designation of \"Expected\".", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a015", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "In such a case, the sponsor may determine whether to include other permissible CP test qualifier variables, based on the needs of the data recipient.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a016", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "This example presents records that might typically be reported for a panel of tests quantifying T-cell, B-cell, monocyte, and natural killer (NK) cell populations, and for subtyping T-cells.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a017", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "In this example, the sponsor determined that none of the permissible CP test qualifier variables were needed to accurately comprehend or distinguish among tests in the dataset, so chose to include only the CPMRKSTR (complete markers string) information.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a018", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Example 1b, in addition to including the expected CPMRKSTR variable, introduces 2 additional variables: CPGATE and CPGATDEF.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a019", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "These variables convey gating information used in data collection and/or analyses, and are often needed to fully understand a test.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a020", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Typically, either the full gating strategy or the penultimate gate is identified.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a021", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "Because different gating strategies for the same test can yield somewhat different test results, the CPGATE and CPGATDEF variables provide the means for transmitting this information at the test (i.e., record) level.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a022", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "Example 1a", "heading_level": 7, "sibling_index": 1, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0208_a023", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 208, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 1-3: The total leukocyte population is determined using positive expression of the CD45 marker as the operational definition of the test (CD45+ in the CPMRKSTR variable). The total leukocyte count is reported because it contains the value used as the denominator in several subsequent tests for leukocyte subpopulations. Row 2 contains the total lymphocyte count which, in addition to CD45, used Forward (FSC) and Side (SSC) Light Scatter properties to define the lymphocyte subpopulation of leukocytes. By convention, FSC and SSC are often not included as part of the marker string definition of a cell subpopulation since it is well-recognized that these physical properties are used as the first gate in nearly all cell phenotyping applications. However, in the absence of a pan-lymphocyte marker to distinguish them from other leukocytes, FSC and SSC are included in rows 2 and 3 to indicate that these parameters are used in addition to CD45, to differentiate lymphocytes from other", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:executor", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_OptionE_executor_rerun_NEW3_outer_pipe_explicit_null_key_M2_sentence_expansion", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a001", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "CD45+ leukocytes. Once they have been included in the marker string (CPMRKSTR) definition of lymphocytes, they can generally be dropped for any further subsetting of the lymphocytes population. Row 3 shows the proportion of lymphocytes as a percentage of total leukocytes. Note that the value in CPMRKSTR used a forward slash (\"/\") to separate the numerator marker string from the denominator marker string.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a002", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 4-5: The B-lymphocyte lineage of lymphocytes is determined using a set of lineage-specific markers in addition to the CD45 leukocyte marker, to define the subpopulation both in terms of positive (i.e., CD19+) and negative (i.e., CD3-, CD14-, and CD56-) marker expression. Following a common convention and CP domain guidance for ordering markers in CPMRKSTR, the marker(s) used to define the highest level of the lineage hierarchy are placed first (i.e., CD45+ defining the leukocyte population), followed by marker(s) that define each subsequently lower level of the hierarchy. The example also follows a convention whereby the set of positive and negative markers used to identify the major lineages of leukocytes are ordered by T-cell, B-cell, monocyte, and NK cell. In row 4, B lymphocytes are defined as leukocytes (CD45+), non-T-cell (CD3-), B-cell (CD19+), non-monocyte (CD14-), and non-NK cell (CD56-), resulting in a CPMRKSTR value of \"CD45+CD3-CD19+CD14-CD56-\". Row 5 shows that CPMRKSTR contains the full set of markers used to define both the numerator and the denominator, separated by a forward slash \"/\".", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a003", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 6-7: The T-lymphocyte lineage of lymphocytes is determined using a set of lineage-specific markers in addition to the CD45 leukocyte marker, to define the subpopulation both in terms of positive (i.e., CD3+) and negative (i.e., CD19-, CD14-, and CD56-) marker expression. The order of markers in CPMRKSTR follows the same convention described for B-lymphocytes in rows 4 and 5.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a004", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 8-11: The T-lymphocyte lineage is divided further into T helper and T cytotoxic sublineages. In these examples the laboratory does not use the negative lineage markers for B-cells, monocytes, and NK cells, but used the positive T-cell (CD3) marker to identify the T-lymphocyte population, and additional markers to define subpopulations as either the T helper (CD4+CD8-) or T cytotoxic (CD4-CD8+) subpopulation. In rows 9 and 11, results are reported as a percentage of the total T-lymphocyte population. Using CPMRKSTR, the numerator is the marker string used to define the T helper subpopulation (as shown in row 8) or the T cytotoxic subpopulation (as shown in row 10), and the denominator consists of the marker string used to define the total T-lymphocyte population (as shown in row 6). A forward slash \"/\" is used to separate the numerator and denominator.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a005", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 12-13: The monocyte lineage of leukocytes is determined using a set of lineage-specific markers in addition to the CD45 leukocyte marker, to define the subpopulation both in terms of positive (i.e., CD14+) and negative (i.e., CD3-, CD19-, and CD56-) marker expression. The order of markers in CPMRKSTR follows the same convention described for B-lymphocytes in rows 4 and 5. In addition, the sponsor chose to include the FSC and SSC properties as markers because they are used, in part, to differentiate the monocyte and lymphocyte populations. Note that when FSC and SSC are used in a marker string, they usually go last, whereas they often come first when showing a gating strategy.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a006", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 14-15: The NK cell lineage of leukocytes is determined using a set of lineage-specific markers in addition to the CD45 leukocyte marker, to define the subpopulation both in terms of positive (i.e., CD56+) and negative (i.e., CD3-, CD19-, and CD14-) marker expression. The order of markers in CPMRKSTR follows the same convention described for B-lymphocytes in rows 4 and 5. In addition, the sponsor chose to include the FSC and SSC properties as markers because they are used, in part, to differentiate the natural killer cell and lymphocyte populations. Note that when FSC and SSC are used in a marker string, they usually go last, whereas they often come first when showing a gating strategy.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0209_a007", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 209, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.5.3 Cell Phenotype Findings (CP)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Row 16: The ratio of T helper to T cytotoxic lymphocytes is calculated from the T helper (CD4+) cell count in row 8 and the T cytotoxic (CD8+) cell count in row 10 and a unit of measure is not included because it is not reported by the lab for this type of test.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_inline_R1-R15_NEW1-NEW7_round3_batch21b", "ts": "2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
