{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISENDY | Study Day of End of Specimen Collection | Num |  | Timing | Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics. | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISTPT | Planned Time Point Name | Char |  | Timing | Text description of time when specimen should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See ISTPTNUM and ISTPTREF. Examples: \"Start\", \"5 min post\". | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISTPTNUM | Planned Time Point Number | Num |  | Timing | Numerical version of ISTPT to aid in sorting. | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISELTM | Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref | Char | ISO 8601 duration | Timing | Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (ISTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable. Represented as ISO 8601 duration. Examples: \"-PT15M\" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by ISTPTREF, \"PT8H\" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by ISTPTREF. | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISTPTREF | Time Point Reference | Char |  | Timing | Name of the fixed reference point referred to by ISELTM, ISTPTNUM, and ISTPT. Examples: \"PREVIOUS DOSE\", \"PREVIOUS MEAL\". | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| ISRFTDTC | Date/Time of Reference Time Point | Char | ISO 8601 datetime or interval | Timing | Date/time of the reference time point, ISTPTREF. | Perm |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"NOTE","verbatim":"1In this column, an asterisk (*) indicates that the variable may be subject to controlled terminology. CDISC/NCI codelist values are enclosed in parentheses.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"IS – Assumptions","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1. The Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS) domain holds assessments that describe whether a therapy (e.g., biologic, drug, vaccine) provoked/caused/induced an immune response in a subject. The response can be either positive or negative. For example, a vaccine is expected to induce a beneficial immune response, whereas a cellular therapy (e.g., erythropoiesis-stimulating agents) may cause an adverse immune response.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0231_a019","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":231,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2. The IS domain also holds assessments that describe whether an allergen, microorganism, or endogenous molecule provoked/caused/induced an immune response in a subject, such as a subject's antibody reaction (autoantibodies) against auto/self-antigens for autoimmune studies or antibody production in response to allergens in allergy trials. Expected outputs can be positive or negative, present or absent for the antibody of interest, as well as quantification of the antibody. Assessments pertaining to antibodies produced in response to microbial infection will also be represented in the IS domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:01Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3. Assessments about all other types of \"induced\" humoral (antibody) immune response in a subject (e.g., antibodies against human leukocyte antigen (HLA) proteins) will also be represented in the IS domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"4. Certain types of cellular immune responses will also be modeled in IS using non-flow cytometry techniques (see example 6). Flow cytometry data should be modeled in the Cell Phenotype Findings (CP) domain, section 6.3.5.3.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["§6.3.5.3"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"5. An exception is made to the class of antigen/antibody (Ag/Ab) combination assays. Microbial antigen/antibody (Ag/Ab) combination tests should be represented in the Microbiology Specimen (MB) domain. An example is fourth-generation HIV Ag/Ab combination tests, which are commonly seen as HIV identification or detection assays rather than tests that provide additional details on and characterization of a subject's immunological responses. The outputs of these assays can be expected as reactive, non-reactive, or indeterminate. Whereas some tests generate separate outputs for antigen and antibody, others just indicate \"reactive\" when either or both are detected. Output is generally based on relative light units, where a result of \"reactive\" typically requires the signal to cutoff ratio to be greater than 1.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"6. Measurements of cytokines, chemokines, and complement proteins should be represented in the Laboratory Test Results (LB) domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"7. The IS domain variable ISBDAGNT (Binding Agent) is currently supported by 2 Controlled Terminology codelists: Microorganism (MICROORG) and Binding Agent for Immunogenicity Tests (ISBDAGT). Controlled Terminology Rules for Immunogenicity Tests describes how and when to use each codelist (see https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a. For antidrug antibody (ADA) tests, the ISBDAGNT variable is used to represent the free-text description of the name/identity of the therapy the antidrug antibody targets. CDISC does not control study therapy names (e.g., drugs, biologics). For ADA tests as a part of regulatory agency submissions, the proprietary binding study therapy name(s) should be considered as extended values of the ISBDAGT codelist when represented in Define-XML.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. For mixed-allergens panel tests, submission values represented in the ISBDAGNT variable should follow this format: “XXX, Multiple” (e.g., Dairy Mix Antigens, Multiple; Animal Mix Antigens, Multiple; use the plural form for the word “antigen” if needed). Should the sponsor wish to specify the individual antigens in a mixed antigens panel (e.g., ISBDAGNT = “Animal Mix Antigens, Multiple”), put the names of the specific antigens in Suppqual (e.g., Cat, Dog, Cow, Horse; see example 11).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"8. The IS domain variable ISTSTOPO (Test Operational Objective) is supported by a nonextensible Controlled Terminology codelist containing the values SCREEN, CONFIRM, and QUANTIFY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"9. For vaccine studies, in order to distinguish collected data between study vaccine-induced immunogenicity and immunogenicity findings unrelated to the study vaccine (i.e., immunity as a result of natural infection or previous vaccination), the following ISCAT and ISSCAT values are recommended (see example 5):","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a. For immunological data pertaining to the study vaccine, ISCAT = STUDY VACCINE-RELATED IMMUNOGENICITY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. For immunological data collected during the vaccine trial but which are not assessments about the study vaccine, ISCAT = NON-STUDY-RELATED IMMUNOGENICITY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"c. For assessments measuring the induced-antibody response, ISSCAT = HUMORAL IMMUNITY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"d. For assessments measuring the induced-cellular response, ISSCAT = CELLULAR IMMUNITY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0232_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":232,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"10. Any Identifier variables, Timing variables, or Findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to the IS domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:02Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"IS – Examples","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"Example 1","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This example shows data from tiered testing of antidrug antibody (ADA).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Tiered testing scheme for ADA evaluation generally includes the following steps: screening, confirmatory, and \"characterization\" of the antidrug antibody.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In tier 1, all evaluable samples are run in a screening assay.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Samples that are positive for ADA in the screen assay are then analyzed in a confirmatory assay (tier 2).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The samples that are positive for ADA in both the screen and confirmatory tiers of testing are further tested in tier 3; this frequently includes analysis of antibody titer and neutralizing activity.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In order to illustrate the distinctive differences between the 3 tiers of ADA testing, the standard variable ISTSTOPO is used to represent the controlled values SCREEN, CONFIRM, and QUANTIFY.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"These values help to describe the operational objective or the reason behind each testing step/tier, and also to provide uniqueness to each row of record.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The study drug AZ-007, which induces the subject's production of, and is the target of the antidrug antibody, is represented by the variable ISBDAGNT.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"ISGRPID is used in this example to show that the records are related to each other; in this particular case, tests are done in a tiered, sequential manner from screen to confirm to quantification of the detected antidrug antibody.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Lastly, antibody titer is often defined as the reciprocal of the lowest dilution of a sample generating a signal that is above the assay cut-point.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Alternatively, the titer is defined as the reciprocal of the dilution of a sample generating a signal that is equivalent to the assay cut-point, calculated by an interpolation formula provided in an assay specific bioanalytical method.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Row 1:     Shows the screening of the presence of ADA to drug AZ-007.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Row 2:     Shows the confirmation of the previously detected ADA to drug AZ-007.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Row 3:     Shows the measurement of titer of the ADA from the screen and confirmatory steps.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
