{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a023","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This example shows data from various subtypes of ADA tests.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a024","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Although most ADAs do not inhibit the pharmacodynamic activity of a drug, neutralizing antidrug antibodies (NAbs) can inhibit drug activity soon after a drug is administered.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a025","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Most ADAs (those that are not classified as NAbs) can lower the drug's systemic exposure by increasing the rate of drug clearance, resulting in a clinically similar outcome to that of NAbs (i.e., reduced clinical efficacy).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a026","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In this example, the administered drug is an analogue of an endogenous protein.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a027","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The example data include ADA reactions against both the administered drug and the endogenous protein.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a028","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Both the study drug and the endogenous protein are represented by the standard variable ISBDAGNT, which qualifies ISTEST.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a029","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The variable ISTSTOPO, is also used in this dataset to describe the purpose of each testing step, and provides uniqueness among similar records.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a030","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Note that, in this example, even though only confirmatory records are reported and shown, it is assumed that the screening step has also been performed.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a031","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 1-2:     Show the confirmation and quantification of binding ADA to coagulation factor VIII analogue drug. A binding antidrug antibody is an antibody that binds to a drug.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0233_a032","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":233,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 3-4:     Show the confirmation and quantification of the neutralizing binding ADA to coagulation factor VIII analogue drug. A neutralizing binding antidrug antibody is a type of ADA that binds to the functional portion of a drug, leading to diminished or negated pharmacological activity. The neutralizing ADAs are a subset of the total ADAs.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:03Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0234_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":234,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 5-6:     Show the confirmation and quantification of the cross-reactive binding ADA to the endogenous coagulation factor VIII. A cross-reactive binding antidrug antibody is a type of ADA that binds to endogenous molecules, also a subset of the total ADAs.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0234_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":234,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 7-8:     Show the confirmation and quantification of the neutralizing cross-reactive binding ADA to the endogenous coagulation factor VIII. Neutralizing cross-reactive binding antidrug antibodies are a type of ADA that bind to endogenous molecules, leading to diminished or negated function; in some cases, they may also bind and negate the function of the study drug. They are a subset of the total ADAs.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:04Z"}}
