{"atom_id":"ig34_p0251_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":251,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii. The result should generally be \"PRESENT\"/\"ABSENT\", \"POSITIVE\"/\"NEGATIVE\", or \"INDETERMINATE\". However, there may be cases where a test differentiates between 2 or more similar organisms, in which case it would be appropriate for the result to be the name of the organism detected. For example, a test may look for influenza A or influenza B antigen. In this case, MBTEST would be \"Influenza A/B Antigen\"; the result could be \"INFLUENZA A ANTIGEN\", \"INFLUENZA B ANTIGEN\", or \"INFLUENZA A/B ANTIGEN\".","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
