{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iv. CDISC Controlled Terminology Rules for Microbiology (MB/MS) domains are available at https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology.","cross_refs":["§6.2.2"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"CROSS_REF","verbatim":"https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3. If the specimen was cultured, the start and end date of culture are represented in the Biospecimen Events (BE) domain in BESTDTC and BEENDTC respectively. The variable --REFID represents the sample ID as originally assigned to the BE domain. See BE domain assumptions in the SDTMIG v3.4, section 6.2.2, for guidelines on assigning --REFID values to samples and subsamples.","cross_refs":["§6.2.2"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a. Culture dates can be connected to the MB record via MBREFID and BEREFID.","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. If the same sample is associated with many biospecimen events and tests, users may need to make use of additional linking variables such as --LNKID.","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.1 Microbiology Specimen (MB)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"4. The variable NHOID is not allowed for use in the MB domain. Any additional Identifiers, Timing variables, or Findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to the MB domain, but the following variables would not generally be used: --MODIFY, --BODSYS, --FAST, --TOX, --TOXGR, --SEV.","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7 Microbiology Domains","atom_type":"HEADING","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":2,"verbatim":"6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"HEADING","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"verbatim":"MS – Description/Overview","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"A findings domain that represents drug susceptibility testing results only. This includes phenotypic testing (where drug is added directly to a culture of organisms) and genotypic tests that provide results in terms of susceptible or resistant. Drug susceptibility testing may occur on a wide variety of non-host organisms, including bacteria, viruses, fungi, protozoa and parasites.","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0252_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":252,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"HEADING","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":2,"verbatim":"MS – Specification","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
