{"atom_id":"ig34_p0255_a039","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":255,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"CODE_LITERAL","verbatim":"MSSTRESU","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0255_a040","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":255,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. Genetic tests that provide results in terms of susceptible/resistant only (e.g., nucleic acid amplification tests (NAAT)). Genotypic tests that provide results in terms of specific changes to nucleotides, codons, or amino acids of genes/gene products associated with resistance should be represented in the Genomic Findings (GF) domain, as that domain structure contains the variables necessary to accommodate data of this type. If a test provides both mutation data and susceptibility data, the mutation results should be represented in GF and the susceptibility information should be represented in MS. In these cases, the GF records should be linked via RELREC to susceptibility records in MS.","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0255_a041","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":255,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"CODE_LITERAL","verbatim":"(NAAT)","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0255_a042","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":255,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"CODE_LITERAL","verbatim":"RELREC","cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T08:15:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i. As in 1.a.ii, MSAGENT should be populated with the drug whose action would be affected by the genetic marker being assessed via the genotypic test. MSCONC and MSCONCU are null in these records.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"c. CDISC Controlled Terminology Rules for Microbiology (MB/MS) domains are available at https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2. MSDTC represents the date the specimen was collected.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3. If the specimen was cultured, the start and end date of culture are represented in the Biospecimen Events (BE) domain in BESTDTC and BEENDTC, respectively.\n--REFID represents the sample ID as originally assigned in the BE domain. See BE domain assumptions in the SDTMIG v3.4, Section 6.2.2, for guidelines on assigning --REFID values to samples and subsamples.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a. Culture dates can be connected to the MS record via MSREFID and BEREFID.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b. If the same sample is associated with many biospecimen events and tests, users may need to make use of additional linking variables such as --LNKID.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"4. NHOID is a sponsor-defined, intuitive name of the non-host organism being tested. It should only populated with values representing what is known about the identity of the organism before the results of the test are determined. It should therefore never be used as a qualifier of result.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.2 Microbiology Susceptibility (MS)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"5. Any Identifiers, Timing variables, or Findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to the MS domain, but the following variables would not generally be used: --MODIFY, --BODSYS, --TOX, --TOXGR --SEV.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7 Microbiology Domains","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"Example 1","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In this example, both a central and a local lab (MBNAM) independently identified Enterococcus faecalis (MBORRES) in a fluid specimen (MBSPEC) taken from the skin (MBLOC) of a subject at visit 1.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The method used by both labs was a solid microbial culture (MBMETHOD).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Because the culture was not targeted to encourage the growth of a specific organism, MBTESTCD/MBTEST = \"MCORGIDN\"/\"Microbial Organism Identification\" and MBORRES represents the name of the organism identified.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"CODE_LITERAL","verbatim":"mb.xpt","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"TABLE_HEADER","verbatim":"Row | STUDYID | DOMAIN | USUBJID | MBSEQ | MBREFID | MBLNKID | MBTESTCD | MBTEST | MBORRES | MBSTRESC | MBNAM | MBSPEC | MBLOC | MBMETHOD | VISITNUM | VISIT | MBDTC","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"1 | ABC | MB | ABC-001-002 | 1 | SPEC01 | 1 | MCORGIDN | Microbial Organism Identification | ENTEROCOCCUS FAECALIS | ENTEROCOCCUS FAECALIS | CENTRAL LAB ABC | FLUID | SKIN | MICROBIAL CULTURE, SOLID | 1 | VISIT 1 | 2005-07-21T08:00","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"2 | ABC | MB | ABC-001-002 | 2 | SPEC01 | 2 | MCORGIDN | Microbial Organism Identification | ENTEROCOCCUS FAECALIS | ENTEROCOCCUS FAECALIS | LOCAL LAB XYZ | FLUID | SKIN | MICROBIAL CULTURE, SOLID | 1 | VISIT 1 | 2005-07-21T08:00","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"After E. faecalis was identified in the subject sample, drug susceptibility testing was performed at each of the labs using both the sponsor's investigational drug and amoxicillin.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a019","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Because an identified organism is the subject of the test, the NHOID variable is populated with \"ENTEROCOCCUS FAECALIS\".","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a020","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Between the 2 labs (MSNAM), a total of 3 susceptibility testing methods were used: epsilometer, disk diffusion, and macro broth dilution (MSMETHOD).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a021","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Epsilometer and disk diffusion both use agar diffusion methods, in which an agar plate is inoculated with the microorganism of interest and either a strip (epsilometer) or discs (disk diffusion) containing various concentrations of the drug are placed on the agar plate.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a022","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The epsilometer test method provides both a minimum inhibitory concentration (MSTESTCD = \"MIC\"), the lowest concentration of a drug that inhibits the growth of a microorganism, and a qualitative interpretation (MSTESTCD = \"MICROSUS\") such as susceptible, intermediate, or resistant.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0256_a023","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":256,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The disk diffusion test method provides the diameter of the zone of inhibition","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0257_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":257,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"(MSTESTCD = \"DIAZOINH\") and a qualitative interpretation such as susceptible, intermediate, or resistant (MSTESTCD = \" MICROSUS\" ). The quantitative and qualitative results are grouped together using MSGRPID.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0257_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":257,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The third method, macro broth dilution, was used to test the specimen at a predefined drug concentration of each of the drugs. When the drug and amount are a predefined part of the test, the variable MSAGENT is populated with the name of the drug being used in the susceptibility test. The variables MSCONC and MSCONCU represent the concentration and units of the drug being used.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0257_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":257,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 1-4: Show the minimum inhibitory concentration and the interpretation result reported from Central Lab ABC from a sample that was tested for susceptibility to the sponsor drug and amoxicillin, using an epsilometer test method.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0257_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":257,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 5-6: Show that Local Lab XYZ found that the sample was susceptible to the sponsor drug at a concentration of 0.5 ug/dL and resistant to amoxicillin at a concentration of 0.5 ug/dL.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0257_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":257,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.7.3 Microbiology Specimen/Microbiology Susceptibility Examples","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 7-10: Show the diameter of the zone of inhibition and the interpretation result reported from Local Lab XYZ from a sample that was tested for susceptibility to the sponsor drug and amoxicillin using a disk diffusion test method.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
