{"atom_id":"ig34_p0265_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":265,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"MI – Assumptions","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0265_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":265,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1. This domain holds findings resulting from the microscopic examination of tissue samples. These examinations are performed on a specimen, usually one that has been prepared with some type of stain. Some examinations of cells in fluid specimens (e.g., blood, urine) are classified as lab tests and should be stored in the Laboratory Test Results (LB) domain. Biomarkers assessed by histologic or histopathological examination (by employing cytochemical/immunocytochemical stains) are stored in the MI domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0265_a019","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":265,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2. When biomarker results are represented in MI, MITESTCD reflects the biomarker of interest (e.g., \"BRCA1\", \"HER2\", \"TTF1\"), and MITSTDTL further qualifies the record. MITSTDTL is used to represent details descriptive of staining results (e.g., \"H SCORE TOTAL SCORE\", \"STAINING INTENSITY\", \"PERCENT POSITIVE CELL\").","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0265_a020","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":265,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3. Any Identifiers, Timing variables, or Findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to the MI domain, but the following qualifiers would generally not be used: --POS, --MODIFY, --ORNRLO, --ORNRHI, --STNRLO, --STNRHI, --STNRC, --NRIND, --LEAD, --CSTATE, --BLFL, --FAST, --DRVFL, --LLOQ, --ULOQ.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0266_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":266,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"MI – Examples","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0266_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":266,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"Example 1","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0266_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":266,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Immunohistochemistry (IHC) is a method that involves treating tissue with a stain that adheres to very specific substances. IHC is the method most commonly used to assess the amount of HER2 receptor protein on the surface of the cancer cells. A cell with too many receptors receives too many growth signals. In this study, IHC assessment of HER2 in samples of breast cancer tissue yielded staining intensity on a scale of 0 to 3+. Staining intensity values of 0 to 1+ were categorized as negative; values of 2+ and 3+ were categorized as positive.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0266_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":266,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Row 1:\tShows a subject with a receptor protein stain intensity value of \"0\", categorized in MIRESCAT as \"NEGATIVE\".","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0266_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":266,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.8 Microscopic Findings (MI)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Row 2:\tShows a subject with a receptor protein stain intensity value of \"2+\", categorized in MIRESCAT as \"POSITIVE\".","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
