{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This example shows concentration data for drug A and a metabolite of drug A from plasma and from urine samples collected pre-dose and after dosing on study days 1 and 11.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"PCTPTREF is a text value of the description of a \"zero\" time (e.g., time of dosing). It should be meaningful. If there are multiple PK profiles being generated, the zero time for each will be different (e.g., a different dose such as first dose, second dose) and, as a result, values for PCTPTREF must be different. In this example, such values for PCTPTREF are required to make values of PCTPTNUM and PCTPT unique (see Section 4.4.10, Representing Time Points).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 4.4.10"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 1-2:\tShow day 1 pre-dose drug and metabolite concentrations in plasma and urine.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 3-4:\tShow day 1 pre-dose drug and metabolite concentrations in urine. Urine specimens may be collected over an interval; both PCDTC and PCENDTC have been populated with the same value to indicate that these specimens were collected at a point in time rather than over an interval.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 5-6:\tShow specimen properties (VOLUME and PH) for the day 1 pre-dose urine specimens. These have a PCCAT value of \"SPECIMEN PROPERTY\".","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
