{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 13-16:\tShow day 11 drug and metabolite concentrations in plasma.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0270_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":270,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.1 Pharmacokinetics Concentrations (PC)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Rows 17-20:\tShow day 11 drug and metabolite concentrations in urine specimens collected over an interval. The elapsed times for urine samples are calculated as the elapsed time (from the reference time point, PCTPTREF) to the end of the specimen collection interval. Elapsed time values that are the same for urine and plasma samples have been assigned the same value for PCTPT. For the urine samples, the value in PCEVLINT describes the planned evaluation (or collection) interval relative to the time point. The actual evaluation interval can be determined by subtracting PCDTC from PCENDTC.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2_round5_inline","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:04Z"}}
